{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}} '''Adah Louise Killion Jenkins''' (April 23, 1901 – May 8, 1973) was a [[Civil rights activist]], musician, and a music critic for the [[Baltimore Afro-American|Afro-American newspaper]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=|title=Mrs. Adah Jenkins, 72, was AFRO music critic|last=|first=|date=May 19, 1973|work=The Afro-American|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> Born and raised in Baltimore, Maryland, Jenkins attended the Teachers Training College, now [[Coppin State University]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=|title=Mrs. Jenkins, music critic, teacher, rites set|last=|first=|date=May 12, 1973|work=The Baltimore Sun|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> Initially teaching in Baltimore City Public Schools, where she became the first Black supervisor of music, Jenkins became a professor of music at Morgan State University.<ref name=":0" /> During the Civil Rights Movement, Jenkins was involved with many activists groups; she helped to organize the Baltimore Interracial Fellowship and she was a charter member of the Baltimore chapter of the [[Congress of Racial Equality]].<ref name=":0" /> She was also a key organizer and picketer in the [[Ford's Grand Opera House|organized protests to integrate Ford's Theater]] in Baltimore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2006-02-18/news/0602180084_1_picket-line-fellowship-house-theater-in-washington|title=Integrating the city's theaters|work=tribunedigital-baltimoresun|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en}}</ref> Jenkins served as music critic for the Afro-American for 23 years until her death at the age of 72 on May 8, 1973.<ref name=":1" />
