{{about||the Bantu language spoken in Cameroon|Basaa language|the Kru language spoken in Liberia and Sierra Leone|Bassa language}} {{Infobox language |name=Basa |altname=Basa-Benue |nativename= |states=[[Nigeria]] |region=[[Benue River]] |ethnicity= |speakers=100,000 |date=1973 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Kainji languages|Kainji]] |fam5=[[Basa languages]] |iso3=bzw |glotto=basa1282 |glottorefname=Basa (Nigeria) |dia1=Basa-Kwomu |dia2=Basa-Makurdi |dia3=Basa-Gurara |dia4=Basa-Kwali }}
'''Basa''', disambiguated as '''Basa-Benue''', and also called ''Abacha, Abatsa, Bassa-Komo, Bassa-Kwomu, Rubasa, Rubassa'', is a [[Kainji language]] spoken in central [[Nigeria]], in the vicinity of [[Bassa, Kogi State|Bassa]], [[Ankpa]], [[Nasarawa, Nasarawa State|Nasarawa]], and [[Kwali]] Local Government Areas and of the city of [[Makurdi]].<ref name=e18/> Blench (2008) notes that Basa-Makurdi, Basa-[[Gurara]], and Basa-Kwali are separate varieties from Bassa of Bassa LGA.
Basa speakers also often speak [[Igala language|Igala]] or [[Nupe language|Nupe]].<ref name=e18/>
