{{Infobox ethnic group| |group = '''Maltese in Belgium''' |flag = {{flagicon|Malta}} {{flagicon|Belgium}} |population= '''378''' <small>(2016)</small> |region1 = |region2 = |pop1 = |pop2 = |langs= [[English language|English]]{{·}}[[French language|French]]{{·}}[[Maltese language|Maltese]]{{·}}[[Italian language|Italian]] |rels= [[Roman Catholicism]] |related-c= [[Maltese diaspora]] }}
'''Maltese in Belgium''' are people from [[Malta]] resident in [[Belgium]], whether permanently or temporarily. They include [[People of Malta|Maltese]] who have acquired [[People of Belgium|Belgian]] citizenship, students and workers with [[International organization]]s.
== Population == Before 2003, the Maltese in Belgium were mostly people married to Belgians who had emigrated to the country or Maltese diplomats. In 2003 the employment of [[Maltese people|Maltese]] nationals with the [[European Union]] (EU) started in earnest in view of Malta's membership of the organisation.
Belgian national statistics show that the number of Maltese in Belgium stood at 252 as of 1 January 2008.<ref name="statbel.fgov.be">{{cite web|url=http://statbel.fgov.be/fr/modules/publications/statistiques/population/nationalite_actuelle_de_la_population_par_commune.jsp |title=Nationalité actuelle de la population par commune |language= fr |publisher=www.statbel.fgov.be |date= |accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> Of these, 159 lived in [[Brussels-Capital Region|Brussels]], 70 in [[Flemish Region|Flanders]] and 23 in [[Wallonia]].<ref name="statbel.fgov.be"/> This represents a significant increase over previous years: in 2005 the number of Maltese in Belgium stood at 133<ref>{{cite web|url=http://statbel.fgov.be/fr/binaries/p202y2005_fr_tcm326-39290.pdf |title=Population et menages |publisher=www.statbel.fgov.be |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref> and at 192 in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://statbel.fgov.be/fr/binaries/p202y2006_fr_tcm326-39292.pdf |title=Population et menages |publisher=www.statbel.fgov.be |accessdate=2013-10-30}}</ref>
A more recent estimate quotes the figure of 400 Maltese in Belgium in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlament.org.mt/file.aspx?f=10666 |title=Kamra tad-Deputati (Malta) |publisher=www.parlament.org.mt |date=2012-07-10 |accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref>
The number of Maltese working with the EU institutions and consultative bodies is of 378 in 2016 (an increase over the 365 in 2013 and 324 in 2010). Of these 291 are permanent. As regards EU agencies, they employ 45 Maltese (increase on 33 in 2013), only one of which is permanent.<ref>[https://maltinfilbelgju.wordpress.com/2017/07/20/numru-ta-maltin-jahdmu-mal-ue-3/ Maltin fil-Belgju]</ref>
== Society == Most of the Maltese are in Belgium because of their employment with the EU. It is in fact estimated that of the 324 Maltese employed with the EU in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pq.gov.mt/PQweb.nsf/06d013e9f9ab0283c12568f50054014f/c1256e7b003e1c2dc12576ee002afbd9?OpenDocument |title=Twegiba ghall-mistoqsija parlamentari numru 15749 |publisher=www.pq.gov.mt |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> around 250 worked in Belgium.<ref name="maltin.be">{{cite web|url=http://www.maltin.be/en.html |title=Maltin fil-Belgju asbl |publisher=www.maltin.be |date= |accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> This is why they consider themselves to [[expatriates]] rather than [[emigrant]]s as was the case with the [[Culture of Malta#Maltese Diaspora|Maltese Diaspora]] in the [[Maltese people#Maltese emigration and expatriation|demographic movements]] of previous generations.
This also explains why most Maltese in Belgium either live in the [[Brussels-Capital Region]] or the municipalities bordering this region, in the area in and around the [[Brussels Ring]].
The 2008 statistics indicate a community that's more or less evenly balanced between the sexes and whose members are predominantly in the 25-40 age groups.<ref name="maltin.be"/>
