{{Infobox language family |name=Tswa–Ronga |region=[[Mozambique]], [[South Africa]], [[Zimbabwe]] |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid languages|Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Bantu languages|Bantu]] |fam6=[[Southern Bantu]] |glotto=tswa1254 |glottorefname=Tswa-Ronga (S.50) }}
The '''Tswa–Ronga languages''' are a group of closely related [[Southern Bantu languages]] spoken in Southern Africa chiefly in southern [[Mozambique]], northeastern [[South Africa]] and southeastern [[Zimbabwe]].{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
==Languages== The group is divided into three main languages:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.ethnologue.com/16/show_family.asp?subid=1936-16 |title=Ethnologue report for Tswa-Ronga (S.50) |publisher=Archive.ethnologue.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref> * [[Tswa language|Tswa]] (''Xitswa''): Hlengwe (Khambana-Makwakwe, Khambani, Lengwe, Lhengwe, Makwakwe-Khambana, Shilengwe), Tshwa (Dzibi-Dzonga, Dzivi, Dzonga-Dzibi, Xidzivi), Mandla, Ndxhonge, Nhayi. Partially intelligible of Ronga [rng] and Tsonga [tso].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/TSC |title=Tswa |publisher=Ethnologue |date= |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref> * [[Ronga language|Ronga]] (''Xironga'') : Konde, Putru, Kalanga. Partially intelligible with Tsonga [tso] and Tswa [tsc].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/rng |title=Ronga |publisher=Ethnologue |date= |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref> * [[Tsonga language|Tsonga]] (''Xitsonga''), : Luleke (Xiluleke), Gwamba (Gwapa), Changana (Xichangana), Hlave, Kande, N’walungu (Shingwalungu), Xonga (Ssonga), Jonga (Dzonga), Nkuna, Songa, Nhlanganu (Shihlanganu).<ref name="ethnologue1">{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/tso |title=Tsonga |publisher=Ethnologue |date= |accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref>
"Tsonga" is used to refer to all three languages,{{cn|date=July 2017}} although often used interchangeably with Changana, the most prestigious of the three. All are recognized as languages, although inherently intelligible.<ref name="ethnologue1"/> The group also contains a variety of other minority languages and dialects which are undocumented and exist in an unwritten form.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
==Writing system== {{Importance section|date=July 2017}}
The ''sintu'' writing system, ''[[Ditema tsa Dinoko]]'' (also known in [[Zulu language|Zulu]] as ''Isibheqe Sohlamvu''), for Southern Bantu languages, is used to represent all Tswa-Ronga languages consistently under one orthography.<ref name=isibheqe.org>{{cite web|url=http://www.isibheqe.org |title=Isibheqe Sohlamvu/Ditema tsa Dinoko |author=isibheqe.org |year=2015 |publisher=isibheqe.org }}</ref> This includes those marginal languages that have never been standardised in the Latin alphabet, such as the "East Sotho" varieties (Pulana, Khutswe and Pai). For example, it contains a specific [[grapheme]] indicating [[retroflex consonant|retroflex]] or "cerebral" consonants, such as the [[retroflex ejective affricate]] occurring here in Pai:
{| class="wikitable" |- !English !''place'' |- !HiPai !''itzau'' | [[File:Itzau.jpg|thumbnail|left|[iʈʂʼaːwu]]] |}
